Per radiologist, this appears to be resolving seroma or hematoma.
#3 Anemia, resolving
#4 Hypertension
#5 Dyslipidemia
PLAN
I have discussed at length with Ms. Alford the role of adjuvant chemotherapy in her stage III adenocarcinoma of sigmoid.  We would recommend FOLFOX6 therapy for a total of 12 cycles.  The cycles are given two-weeks apart.  I have discussed the side-effects including, but not limited to, myelosuppression, life-threatening infection including death, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, cardiac toxicity of 5-FU, hand/foot syndrome, stomatitis, neuropathy related to oxaliplatin (both acute and cumulative neurotoxicity), and nephrotoxicity.  I have suggested that she take her antihypertensive medications regularly since she missed her dose today.  She does have some postoperative fluid collection noted on her CT-scan of the abdomen today.  We will recheck a CT-scan in about three-months' time.  We do not believe this would be a contraindication to chemotherapy.  This has been discussed with Dr. Trujillo.  She indicated that she would get her chemotherapy closer to home and would notify us of her oncologist as soon as she finds one.  Meanwhile, she will contact Dr. Rivera's Service if she has any wound-related issues. Ordered k-ras mutation test. Results are  pending currently.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at Montezuma Medical Center.

