[start section id="20103"]

Ms. Alford is a very pleasant 69-year-old lady from Rhoadesville, Acworth who is accompanied today by her 20856 cousin.  She is here to discuss about the treatment recommendations following resection of a T1, N1 sigmoid grade 3 adenocarcinoma.  Ms. Alford' oncologic history is outlined below:
April 16, 2010, on a routine colonoscopy examination she was found to have 50% to 60% circumferential, flat, nodular area at 18 to 20 cm that was friable and would bleed at touch.  This was biopsied and found to be tubular adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.  It was not amenable to endoscopic removal.There was another 3-mm polyp in the ascending colon that was tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia.  In addition, she had multiple sigmoid diverticulosis.
May 4, 2010, a proctoscopy was performed noting a polypoid lesion at 15 to 16 cm.  It was again not amenable to endoscopic removal, and on May 26 she underwent laparoscopic low-anterior resection.
Per operative report, exploration of the abdomen found no abnormalities, and the pathology of the rectosigmoid tissue was positive for moderately differentiated grade 3 adenocarcinoma.  Tumor was noted to arise in the tubulovillous adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.  The surgical margins were negative.  Tumor invaded into the submucosa (T1).  All resected margins were negative, and of 15 regional lymph nodes, only 1 was positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma (pT1, N1).
Today, she is nearly slightly over four weeks out from her surgery and is here regarding adjuvant therapy.  Notably, she has been evaluated by our radiation oncology colleagues and has not been found to be a candidate for radiation therapy since it is a sigmoid adenocarcinoma primarily.  She states that her last colonoscopy was about two decades ago.  Over the last few months she had noticed some loose bowel movements with certain kinds of food along with some bloating sensation with spicy food.  Unfortunately, her sister recently passed away from ovarian cancer.  She denies any nausea, vomiting, abdominal distention, chest pain, shortness-of-breath, loss of appetite, early satiety, palpitations, fever, or chills.  She did notice some discharge at the site of incision and was seen by Dr. Rivera today.  Apparently, there was an area of fluid collection (seroma) from which fluid has been expressed today by Dr. Rivera, and it is packed.  There is also some redness at the site of incision that she noticed in the last few weeks.

